        <div class="commentcontent">
            <p>Great post. The instructions are accurate, even though one of the steps can be simplified a bit for noobs. A couple of clarifications:</p>

<p>1. What you did is root the phone, not jailbreak it. Unlike the iPhone, Google and HTC give you a legal path to replace key components of the phone software without breaking the law/breaching a contract. The warranty is voided, but it seems it is a price that a lot of people are willing to pay for the additional benefits that rooting obtains. Also, there has been a report in one of the forums of an incident in which HTC replaced a rooted device due to a hardware malfunction for no charge.</p>

<p>2. Google has previously C&D'd a hacker called JesusFreak (or some such) for distribution the Google apps. You're linking to to that, which is I think they could find a bit problematic...</p>

<p>As an aside, you can follow pretty much the install an alpha of the HTC Desire ROM on the Nexus One (I did). Besides a few minor snags, it works flawlessly. More importnatly, the sight of Sense UI is clear to eschew tremors from nearby geeks. Some of the HTC apps are better than Google's, and going back to Cyanogen is pretty simple.</p>

<p>You might want to avoid publishing this comment. Perfectly understandable... :)</p>
		</div>
	</div>



        
    
        
